      title: '<p style="text-align: center;">D</p><p><zmindent contenteditable="false">空类0</zmindent>We may think we&#39;re&nbsp;a&nbsp;culture that&nbsp;gets rid of our worn technology at the first&nbsp;sight of something shiny and new, but a new study shows that we keep using our old devices（装置）well&nbsp;after they go&nbsp;out of style. That&#39;s bad&nbsp;news for the environment -and our wallets -as these outdated devices consume much more energy than the newer ones&nbsp;that do the same&nbsp;things.</p><p><zmindent contenteditable="false">空类0</zmindent>To figure out how much power these&nbsp;devices are using.&nbsp;Callie Babbitt&nbsp;and her colleagues at&nbsp;the Rochester lnstitute&nbsp;of Technology in New York tracked the environmental costs for each product throughout&nbsp;his life-from where&nbsp;its minerals are mined to when&nbsp;we stop using the device. This method provided a&nbsp;readout for&nbsp; how home&nbsp;energy use has evolved since the early&nbsp;1990s. Devices were grouped by generation&nbsp;Desktop&nbsp;computers, basic mobile&nbsp;phones,and&nbsp;box-set TVs defined 1992&nbsp;.Digital&nbsp;cameras arrived on the scene in 1997. And MP3 players,&nbsp;smart phones, and LCD TVs entered homes in 2002, before tablets and e-readers showed up in 2007.</p><p><zmindent contenteditable="false">空类0</zmindent>As we accumulated more devices, however, we didn&#39;t throw&nbsp;out our old ones. &quot;The living-room television&nbsp;is replaced and gets planted in the kids&#39; rooms and suddenly&nbsp;one day, you have a TV in every room&nbsp;of the house.&quot; said one researcher. The average&nbsp;number of electronic&nbsp;devices rose from four per household in 1992 to I3 in 2007. We&#39;re pot just keeping these old devices-we continue to use them.&nbsp;According to the analysis of Babbitt&#39;s&nbsp;team, old monitors and box TVs with&nbsp;cathode ray tubes are the worst devices with their energy consumption and contribution to greenhouse gas emissions（排放）more than doubling during the 1992 to 2007 window.</p><p><zmindent contenteditable="false">空类0</zmindent>So what&#39;s the solution（解决方案）! The team&#39;s date only went up to 2007, bus the researchers&nbsp;also explored&nbsp;what would happen if consumers replaced old products with new electronics that serve more than one function, such as a tablet fer word processing and TV Viewing.&nbsp;They found that&nbsp;&nbsp;more on demand entertainment, &nbsp;viewing on tablets instead of TVs and desktop computers could cut energy consumption by 44%.</p>',
